The only additional workload the default_function add to are consistency checks, for example. If we compile a function that only accepts tensor of size ```(4,4)```, it checks

```c++
void default_function(DLTensor *v) {
   CHECK(v->shape[0] == 4);
   CHECK(v->shape[1] == 4);
   default_compute_function(v);
}
```

We can modify the MakeAPI function to not emit those checks, and expose the risk to the user. However, 
such check should not really affect FLOPS number you get for the general operator of interest, so it is really not necessary to do the raw function calls. 

For example, compiling a CPU kernel and a CUDA kernel will have the same default checks, but you can observe very different FLOPS, in terms of TFLOPS to GFLOPS level, this indicate that the checks are not the bottleneck at all.

